  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish common standards and frameworks for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate through extradition and evidence-sharing agreements\n- Allows prosecution of cross-border money laundering activities\n- Enables tracking of financial transactions across jurisdictions\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align domestic laws with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n- Similar investigative and prosecutorial approaches\n- Promotes more effective global enforcement\n\n5. Information Exchange Mechanisms\n- International financial intelligence units\n- Interpol and other transnational law enforcement networks\n- Electronic platforms for rapid information sharing\n\n6. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Pressure to adopt robust AML frameworks\n- Financial penalties for inadequate regulation\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally.",
